physdesc.physfacet: Media guides, game programs, news releases, newspaper clippings, photographs, negatives, ephemera, and artifacts in fair condition with noticeable aging to older material

did.abstract: This collection consists of annual reports, media guides, sporting event programs, news releases, newspaper clippings, photographs, negatives, video cassettes, ephemera, and artifacts retained by the Central Washington University's Athletics Department from 1923 to 2023.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The Athletics Department at Central Washington University dates back to 1893 with the introduction of a Physical Culture class at the Washington State Normal School and with the first women’s basketball game played in 1895. Throughout the 1890s and early 1900s, the men’s and women’s basketball teams played local and regional high schools. In 1909 the Normal School hired a part-time athletics coach to manage the growing number of sports teams. Later that same year, the men’s basketball team played Bellingham Normal School (Western Washington University), making it the first inter-collegiate sporting event in the school’s history. The athletics program served as part of the Department of Health and Physical Education until 1983 when it became its own independent department.

scopecontent.p: The bulk of the material in this collection dates from the late 1960s to the early 1990s. Significant items in the collection include basketball programs during the Dean Nicholson era, team photographs, game scorebooks dating back to 1948, videos of football games during 1990s, women’s basketball games during the early 2000s, championship banners and letter jackets.
Since 2014 most Athletics information is born digital. These electronic materials can be accessed on computers in the archives reading room.

odd.p: Central Washington University began as the Washington State Normal School in 1891. In 1937, the school was rechristened the Central Washington College of Education. In 1961, the school became Central Washington State College and, finally, in 1977, Central Washington University.

arrangement.p: Organized into eleven series: I. Annual reports; II. Media guides; III. Newspaper clipping and news releases IV. Programs; V. Programs, basketball; VI. Scorebooks; VII. Miscellaneous records; VIII. Photographs and negatives; IX. Video cassettes; X. Oversized. XI. Scrapbooks. Alphabetically arranged by subject heading of file folder.

accessrestrict.p: Open to the public for educational research.
